text:
Our flight arrived late but we still wanted to grab a bite (it was after 11pm) and the hotel employee recommended Oceana Grill. We ordered a variety of appetizers and entrees...
Crab Meat Cakes (really good and not too salty; cream sauce was yummy);
Gator Tail Bites (Half & Half)...we liked the fried much more than the grilled; 
Taste of New Orleans: we tried others restaurants' étouffée and my friend likes OG's the best; 
Fried Crawfish Tails: loved it; very delicious

We would definitely return to Oceana Grill!

Best food Period in New Orleans!!! We know the chef Nick Allen who brought our Food out to our Table personally.. Each dish got Better & Better .. From our Appetizer to our Entree & dessert!!! We compared everyone to this place the entire Jazz Festival 2015 ... You can't go wrong with Oceana  & tell Chef Nick   
"Ash to ash, dust to dust, bloods I trust;
Crabs we bust, kill a crab, win a prize!!!

A-OKAY, BUT NOT WORTH WAITING IN LINE FOR
2,073 reviews for Oceana and I bet, like Acme, 90% queued for a table. Sure the efficient staff are friendly and prices are moderate but the seafood is just average (pic). Opt for these comparable nearby alternatives if you can't get seated:

1. "Desire" - affordable, classic tile and panel Creole café, career employees, sit at the shucker bar;
2. "MRB's"- a neighborhood favorite, bar food with excellent char-grilled oysters;
3. "Deanie's" - Applebeesish, reasonably priced adequate seafood;
4. "New Orleans Hamburger & Seafood" - kid friendly local chain, get the garlic fries;
5. "Royal House" - seafood's a tad over priced, sit on the romantic balcony.
And if someone else is paying:
6. "GW Fins"; or if lucky
7. "Pêche".

REGARDLESS, REFUSE TO SIT IN THE REAR!
Don't let them entomb you in their claustrophobic back room. If you are going to wait an hour for a table you should hold out for the main dining area.

